            "content": "Gold-plated sterling silver is a type of jewelry and decorative item that combines two precious metals: gold and sterling silver. Sterling silver is an alloy consisting of 92.5% silver and 7.5% other metals, usually copper, which enhances its strength and durability. The 'gold-plated' aspect refers to a thin layer of gold that is applied to the surface of the sterling silver item. This layer is typically applied through a process known as electroplating, where an electric current is used to deposit a thin layer of gold onto the silver. The thickness of the gold layer can vary, but it is generally very thin, often measured in microns. This combination allows for the appearance and prestige of gold at a lower cost, while also benefiting from the structural integrity of sterling silver. Gold-plated sterling silver is popular in the jewelry market due to its affordability compared to solid gold items, while still providing a luxurious appearance.",
            "relevance_score": 0.9
        },
