            "content": "The conceptual design phase is marked by several key properties and characteristics that distinguish it from other stages of the design process. One of the primary attributes is its focus on abstraction and simplification. Designers work with high-level concepts and avoid getting bogged down by technical details, which allows for greater flexibility and creativity. Another characteristic is the iterative nature of conceptual design. Designers often cycle through multiple iterations, refining and evolving their ideas based on feedback and new insights. This iterative process is essential for exploring a wide range of possibilities and identifying the most promising solutions. Additionally, conceptual design is inherently collaborative, involving input from various stakeholders, including clients, engineers, and end-users. This collaboration ensures that the design is feasible, desirable, and viable. Tools commonly used in this phase include brainstorming sessions, mind mapping, and sketching, all of which facilitate the free flow of ideas and encourage innovative thinking.",
